******
[1] Uganda, Rakai, prevention measures in cattle
Date: Thu 9 Aug 2018
Source: Monitor (Kampala, Uganda) [summ., edited]
http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Four-Rakai-cattle-markets-closed-over-fever-outbreak/688334-4704338-ov0qubz/index.html


Rakai veterinary specialists and leaders have closed 4 major cattle markets in the district following an outbreak of Rift Valley Fever (RVF) in neighbouring Isingiro district. Two people and 7 cows have already died of the fever. The closed markets include Ddyango and Kamuli in Kyalulangira and Kiziba sub-counties, respectively. Others are Kacheera and Lwamagwa livestock markets.

Livestock farmers in Kyalulangira, under their umbrella body Nyekundire Farmers' Association, say the district authorities had been reluctant to close the markets in the past month over revenue.

"We have been telling them to close the markets, but they were looking at revenue likely to be lost. People's health is more important than the targeted revenue from cattle traders. Even the foot and mouth disease could have been contained a long time ago if those people [district authorities] were vigilant," Mr Robert Kanyete, the association chairperson, said in an interview on Tuesday [7 Aug 2018].

The district veterinary officer, Mr Erias Kizito Nsubuga, said the closure of the markets followed a directive from the anti-stock safety unit to control the spread. "RVF has not yet extended to Rakai, but we closed the markets to prevent it from spreading to our district since traders buy cattle from different farms, including those in Isingiro," Dr Nsubuga said.

He added that they also temporarily imposed a ban on the slaughter of cattle and sale of dairy products such as milk as they monitor the situation. He said the fever will not spread to the district due to their robust surveillance system. "We have capacity in responding to outbreaks, and we have proved that over the years," he said. Livestock farmers have suffered unending outbreaks of FMD since 2015, prompting government to place them under quarantine.

According to World Health Organisation (WHO), [RVF] can be transmitted to people either by tick bites or contact with infected animal blood or tissues during and immediately after slaughter.

[byline: Wilson Kutumba and Al-Mahdi Ssenkabirwa]

