******
[2] Kenya, spread to Kilifi's cattle
Date: Fri 10 Aug 2018
Source: The Star (Kenya) [edited]
https://www.the-star.co.ke/news/2018/08/10/quarantine-in-kilifi-amid-rift-valley-fever-outbreak_c1799931


The county government of Kilifi has issued a quarantine against the movement of livestock in Magarini and Malindi sub-counties following cases of Rift Valley fever [RVF]. County executive committee member for agriculture, livestock, and fisheries Luciana Sanzua confirmed on Wednesday [8 Aug 2018] that 16 goats and 2 cattle have died of RVF.

Speaking at the governor's office, Sanzua also confirmed that 17 abattoirs and 4 slaughter slabs have been shut down in the 2 sub-counties. "There were reported cases of abortions in animals in 2 private farms and 2 homesteads in the 2 sub-counties. Abortions in animals is the main clinical sign of RVF in animals; thus, these were handled as suspected cases. Blood samples were taken from the animals and submitted to the Central Veterinary Laboratory-Kabete-Nairobi. This was on [Thu 12 Jul 2018]. We received the results on [Mon 30 Jul 2018]; 18 out of the 78 samples turned positive," said Sanzua. She said the spread was a result of the heavy rains and subsequent flooding in the 2 sub-counties.

The department has since embarked on the spraying of animals with acaricide (chemical), which kills the type of mosquito that breeds in flooded areas and is the type responsible for incubation and starting off of the chain of transmission. "We imposed the quarantine last week to avoid the spread of the disease to other areas. We have also restricted the movement of livestock from Tana River and Garissa counties to our county. Our surveillance team is on the ground, and we urge members of the public to avoid red meat for the time being," added Sanzua. The department of health has also closed down butcheries in the 2 sub-counties.

On Wednesday [8 Aug 2018], health county executive committee member Anisa Omar said no cases of human infection have been reported in the county. She said all health workers have been put on a 24-hour surveillance. "All our medical officers in our health facilities have been instructed to screen anyone who may present with symptoms of RVF. We also urge members of the public to sleep in mosquito-treated nets to keep off the vector," she said.

According to WHO, there is some evidence that humans may become infected with RVF by ingesting the unpasteurized or uncooked milk of infected animals. The majority of human infections result from direct or indirect contact with the blood or organs of infected animals. The virus can be transmitted to humans through the handling of animal tissue during slaughtering or butchering, assisting with animal births, conducting veterinary procedures, or from the disposal of carcasses or foetuses. Certain occupational groups, such as herders, farmers, slaughterhouse workers, and veterinarians, are therefore at higher risk of infection.

The virus infects humans through inoculation, for example via a wound from an infected knife or through contact with broken skin, or through inhalation of aerosols produced during the slaughter of infected animals.

[byline: Elias Yaa]

